Adult/immature.description: Willow Flycatchers have prominent wingbars and have a grayish head, whereas Eastern Phoebes lack wingbars and have a dark brown head.
Eastern Wood-Pewees tend to perch much higher in trees and rarely wag their tails as Eastern Phoebes do. Wood-pewees have stronger wingbars than Eastern Phoebes.

Adult (Northern).description: Black Phoebes have a blackish head and breast and Eastern Phoebes have a gray head and whitish breast.

Adult/immature.description: Say's Phoebes have a peachy belly and gray throat while Eastern Phoebes have a white belly and whitish throat.

Adult (Slate-colored).description: Dark-eyed Juncos have stubby, seed-eating bills and Eastern Phoebes have thin insect-catching bills. Juncos forage on or near the ground in a horizontal posture while phoebes perch upright on branches of trees and shrubs.
